comments.body:
@rhatdan we could also do that, all it would take in addition then would be the id that the remote store uses.

I guess we would need a dedicated import method on the secret manager though.

I thought the semantic would be much clearer if we give that functionality a new verb

It sounds interesting. It seems like this can just use the List() method of a driver, and parse the results, and then make a note of all the available secrets. There has to be checking for duplicates of secret id's too. I don't think allowing arbitrary id's and relaxing of id's is a good idea though, since we want the id's to match what kind of id's docker uses. 

I'm still a little wary, since I'm not too sure of the added complexity. The design of secrets originally was that the secrets store sits on top of the driver store and manages it, but this seems like it would need to go the other way a little. We would also need validation etc, and to make sure the id format remains compatible with docker. 

@vrothberg wdyt?

@vrothberg I think you got one thing wrong: we don't have to touch the secret driver interface. All that would be needed is a new function in the secret manager that imports a secret. This action would just take the driver, driver options and a secret id as used in the backend and write that into the secret metadata store. That method *could* call the driver to validate that the secret exists, but that wouldn't be technically needed.
So this change wouldn't need to be considered when adding new or maintaining existing drivers.

I totally agree that we can not have dedicated drivers for all possible backends, but with things like the shelldriver (which will probably make it into common@0.41.0) we can make it very convenient to integrate them. Sure users could write import scripts, but my feeling is that it would cause less friction if secrets can be imported because once imported, they always stay up to date + there is one less layer of secret caching that may cause secrets to leak.
